It's officially in the logbook. I have 2.3 flight hours ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I had to describe what it's like to fly a small aircraft, I would say it's like a mix of a motorcycle/quad and a boat, 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, you're immediately very fast. Everything is somewhat unstable on the ground, hence motorcycle/quad.
And if you didn't know yet: You steer an airplane on the ground with your feet, not with the control yoke. Rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
In the air, it's wobbly and you're somewhat floating. It feels like being in a boat on water. You can steer it, but sometimes a wave comes and throws you slightly off course, so you have to get used to the sea conditions, only this time in the air.
Another random detail:
Flying is physically demanding. Today, my back and legs hurt *as if* I had been at the gym.
This is not like a Sunday drive in a car. It's more of a sport than a walk, in my newly gained opinion.
A beautiful Saturday, my loves. Welcome to 4,000 feet.
Tomorrow I'm going back. Then we'll practice stall and slow flying.
Today the weather was unsettled, but it was a lot of fun. We practiced slow flying and stall. Once we had a ground speed of only 16 mph at a flight speed of 65.
It was a beautiful clear day, a bit hazy a bit higher up, but still beautiful.
